    <text>
        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>March 24<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1884<lb/>
                New York<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr <sic>Moris</sic><lb/>
                Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>It was through your<lb/> kind intercession that I received<lb/> an engagement as principal Heb<lb/>rew master of the Free school of<lb/> London. I am at present in<lb/> a much worse position than<lb/> I have been at that time &#38; <del>muc</del><lb/> much more in need of your charitable&#44;<lb/> &#38; benevolent interposition. I have no<lb/> doubt that you will not hesitate<lb/> to interfere in my behalf.<lb/></p>
            <p>I was obliged to leave London on<lb/> account of the climate which in&#45;<lb/>jured my health greatly.<lb/></p>
            <p>I went from there to Paris<lb/> where I remained until<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>&#40;2&#41;<lb/></p>
            <p>the persecution against the<lb/> Jews of Russia broke out.<lb/></p>
            <p>It was there that my brother<lb/> a student of that country and quite<lb/> a distinguished journalist urged<lb/> me to go to the U.S. &#38; devote my time<lb/> &#38; my experience to the cause of<lb/> the persecuted. In complying with<lb/> his request I have brought upon<lb/> myself so much misery &#38; humiliation<lb/> that it makes me involuntarily<lb/> regret to ever have been engaged<lb/> in the good cause. I was a member<lb/> of the first colony established<lb/> in <sic>Luisiana</sic> which so miserably<lb/> perished in its infancy.<lb/></p>
            <p>I am at present in New York<lb/> without a position &#38; without means.<lb/> You will oblige me very much<lb/> by recommending me for some<lb/> position in my branch.<lb/></p>
            <p>Besides my knowledge<lb/> of the Hebrew &#38; the<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>&#40;3&#41;<lb/></p>
            <p>Talmud I speak <sic>german</sic><lb/> French &#38; English quite<lb/> fluently.<lb/></p>
            <p>I think I could boldly<lb/> undertake to preach in<lb/> English if insisted upon.<lb/></p>
            <p>I should willingly come<lb/> to Philadelphia to talk to<lb/> you personally about it<lb/> but unfortunately I have<lb/> not the means to do so &#38;<lb/> I am even in debt for a few<lb/> dollars. I have als&#91;o&#63;&#93; appealed<lb/> to Dr Jastrow for that pur<lb/>pose. You would oblige me<lb/> by communicating with him<lb/> on that subject.<lb/></p>
            <p>Hoping you will with your<lb/> habitual &#91;&#63;&#93; &#38; complaisance<lb/> exercise your influence in<lb/> behalf of a fellow man in<lb/> distress&#44; I remain<lb/></p>
            <p>Most sincerely yours<lb/>
                A. Rabinowitz<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="4"/>
            <p>My address is as follows<lb/>
                A. <hi rend="underline">Rabinowitz</hi><lb/>
                care of S. Graboff<lb/>
                79 Chatham Street<lb/>
                New <hi rend="underline">York</hi><lb/></p>
        </body>
